According to my source, Bently, in Shakespeare: a Biographical
Handbook, of the 300 or so authors who contributed to Elizabethan
drama, there were &quot;professional playwrights who made their living by
keeping actors supplied with plays,&quot; which they prepared in close
cooperation with them, but &quot;only a few who were more fully involved in
theatrical affairs, (who) not only wrote plays but acted in them: the
actor-dramatists Thomas Heywood, William Rowley, Nathan Field, and
William Shakespeare.&quot;

Bently notes that Shakespeare was more &quot;theater-tainted&quot; than other
famous dramatists, such as Thomas Kyd, Christopher Marlowe, John Lyly,
Ben Jonson, George Chapman, John Webser, John Fletcher, and James
Shirley&quot; because he is the only one &quot;who is known to have been, over a
long period of years, a theater owner.&quot;

So Shakespeare was playwright, actor, acting company &quot;sharer,&quot; and
theater owner (housekeeper).

bookburn

