A heck of an actor if S as only a figurehead managed to work closely
with play troupes in successfully creating and producing box office
plays, much less standing in as a monument for the real Shakespeare.
Even so, the Bard got the money and the fame; so who upstaged who in
the fakeSpeare go-around?

I'm afraid there would be a point of diminishing returns and muse
failure for anyone laboriously ghost writing popular plays over the
years without recognition. In Sherlock Holmes mysteries you're
supposed to be able to figure out motive, aren't you? Bentley's
biographical handbook suggests that Stratman was a successful
businessman with a multi-faceted career. So what success or
motivation did any alternate candidate have besides monument building?
Is it an iconoclast like Professor Moriarty who steals someone's good
name and just deserts? bb

