His works would get published (and praised to the hilt for centuries)
such that &quot;his children&quot; would be immortal:
---------------------------------------------------------------
&lt;&lt;Besides Lyly &amp; Munday another writer, Thomas CHURCHYARD,
claimed to have been in Oxford's service and twice advertised
his plans to dedicate a book to his patron.&gt;&gt; - Steven May
----------------------------------------------------------------
&lt;&lt;Thomas CHURCHYARD, a hack poet of meager education, writes:

&quot;...numbers of bookes I haue printed: and because they
shall not be buried with me, I challenge them all as my children
to abide behinde me in the worlde, to make them inheritors
of such fame &amp; dispraise as their father (which begat them on sweet
inuention) heere enioyes or deserues: hoping they shall not be
called bastards, nor none aliue will be so hardy as to call them
his babes, that I haue bred in my bowels, brought forth and fostred
vp so carefully at mine owne charge, and hazard of an enuious worlde.&quot;&gt;&gt;

From &quot;Master W. H., R.I.P.&quot; by Donald Foster, PMLA 102, (1987), 42-54
