The monument was vandalized in 1974, and
the opportunity was taken to refurbish the
whole thing. Before this, there was a question
mark after the word 'FAST', a colon after the
word 'DIDE', and the word you noticed was
indeed 'CANST' as one might have expected.
A very clear illustration of what it looked like
before 1974 is given in J.O. Halliwell-Phillipps
*Outlines of a Life of Shakespeare&quot; (1896),

It is just possible, I suppose, that the people
responsible for the refurbishment found it odd
to suggest that someone who was *already*
reading the epitaph would be unable to carry
on doing so. In this case they might have
thought it better to tell them to carry on if
they had already *begun* to read, which
'ganst' could (at a stretch) have meant. It
would be the 2nd person singular of the
word 'gan', as used for example, in *Venus
and Adonis*:

&quot;O pity,&quot; gan she cry, &quot;flint-hearted boy!
'Tis but a kiss I beg - why art thou coy?&quot;

Given that those responsible also managed to

put the two little cherubs (putti) back the

wrong way round (which it took three years

for anyone to notice!) however, I am more

inclined to think that it was just a mistake.

