IF there had been those 25 actors, as well
as all the bit players, ticket-sellers, etc.,
then you'd have a case. But there wasn't --
or we have little or no evidence that there
was a company regularly performing the
canonical plays to public audiences from
the early or mid-1590s onwards. Only 7
public performances plus one sequence
(15 of 1Henry6) are recorded. Some of
those records are uncertain and may be
forged.

In any case, the canonical plays were, by
that time, quite old. The actors would not
have expected to meet the playwright, any
more than their 20th century equivalents
would have expected to meet, say, Arthur
Miller in the late 1980s.

