Thanks, Buffalo. You beat me to the punch, and your reply was much more
succinct than mine probably would have been. So allow me to elaborate :)

It's true there's not MUCH evidence, Paul. But the published plays and
testimonials comprise more real, documentary, evidence than we have for any
English Renaissance playwright except, I suppose, Jonson. Renaissance lit
scholars would be in heaven if they had so much evidence for most
playwrights of the era.

I don't pretend that my speculation about the players' reaction to the
ignoramus posing as an author in their midst is evidence. It's a logical
inference, in the absence of evidence, based on your premise: If we accept
the theory that (insert candidate name here) wrote the plays, then certain
things (players discovering the hoax, candidate remaining silent for
decades) seem likely to have happened. Scholars use this all the time
(e.g., when trying to trace the sources of the plays), but it's the sort of
thing you use when you run out of real evidence.

Unless I'm mistaken, there's NO documentary evidence for the
anti-Stratfordian case. No contemporary attributions of the plays to
someone else; no complaints about Shakespeare usurping authorship; heck, no
one even even expresses doubts about Shakespeare's capability to write the
plays (don't let's start up with Greene again, okay? He's equivocal at
best, way-early, and a grouch to boot). Although it was not really my
intention to fight fire with fire, it's worth noting that my posts offer
some logical inference and circumstantial evidence on the pro-Stratford side
(there is much more, of course). Since your case is built entirely on this
sort of evidence, I should think you'd find it more persuasive.

This seems like a good place to point out that my comments in another thread
about the theatricality of the plays was in no way intended as serious
evidence. I refuted it myself (or attemped to, at any rate) in an unrelated
posting, when I said something like &quot;The author of the plays, whoever he
was, was a singular genius - who's to say what he was not capable of?&quot; If
we had evidence that Derby - my personal fave, he's dreamy - wrote the
plays, I'd dismiss my gabbling by waving Derby's First Folio under my nose.

It's fun to talk about all of this (I like a good conspiracy theory as much
as the next guy) and I enjoy arguing with you all. But I don't think we can
pretend that the basic cases are equal. If you want to have the
anti-Stratfordian case taken seriously, you'll need to come up with SOME
kind of documentary evidence of equal weight to the Stratfordian. As I
said, it's not much, but it weighs a lot more than nothing at all.
