There are very many phonetic ones,considerable amounts of them, not
exclusively:-

There is a clear precedent of GAN; from Chaucer, in the same sense of the
cit. below, meaning &quot;began&quot;.

After this stem~ word there are varieties of spelling, eg: GANE: (1) gone,
went [North], (2) to yawn, or gape [Palsgrave] and still used in
Lincolnshire, pronounced /gawn/. GANG: also means 'to go' [North] ... hence
GANGDAYS; rogation week, so-called because parish boundaries were generally
perambulated at that time. There is an old ref:

Thorow grace that He us 3eveth,
Where so we gange.
/MS. Cantab. Ff. ii. 38, f. 31.

GANSE: (1) thin, slender [Kent]. (2) merriment, hilarity [Sussex]
GANT: (1) to yawn (2) Lusty, hearty (3) a village fair or wake (4) scanty
[Moor's Suffolk Words, p. 143] (4) a gander, &quot;A gose and gant&quot; [Skelton, i.
111. Giraldus Cambrebsis calls it /auca/, the same as /anser/. In Pr. Parv.
/bistarda/ or the bustard according to Ducange. Douce says /gant/ is the
gannet, a bird about the size of a goose, mentioned by Ray as found in
Cornwall.]

GANZAS: geese [Span.]

GAUNT: (1) to yawn [Northumb.] (2) the old English name for Ghent.

GAUN: (1) a gallon measure (2) going, given [North]

GAWNE: gave; still in use in Essex circa 1850.
GAWL: gold [Somerset]

However, there is also a collection of phonetically similar words, all
meaning 'simpleton', GAWNEY, eg.

