This comes up now and again, and there seems to be an idea around that
nobody ever used a mark if they could write. That is not so - there
could be other reasons to use a mark. I can produce an example.

Levi Fox, 'A Country Grammar School' (Oxford for the Governors of the
Foundation, Ashby-de-la-Zouch, 1967) reprints the school accounts,
which include the resolutions authorising some of the items. One of 30
April 1616 ends:

In witness whereof wee have set our handes to this note of
remembraunce the yeare and day above-written
Arth; Hildersam; Thomas Sherwood
Rob; Bainbrigg Rob; Clerk
Rob; Newton Will; Ash
Nich; Hasky John Ash

(The columns are neat, but may well lose their neatness in
transmission!)

Another of 17 September 1616 ends without the 'in witness' bit:

Arth; Hildersam Robert Clark
Robert Bainbrigg John Ash
Robert Newton William ^ Ashes mark
Nicholas Haskey Thomas &amp; Sherwoods mark

(The &amp; is only an approximation to the complicated squiggle Sherwood
used.)

Plainly William Ashe and Thomas Sherwood could write, but in the
second case the secretary had to go and find them and get them to sign
out of order (the signatures are usually in strict order of seniority)
perhaps at some time or place where it was not at all convenient (in
the street? at the cattle-market?). So very likely they here used
marks because it was so much quicker and easier. Evidently their marks
were known - this will not have been the only time they used them.

