Yes. You're getting there. Remember that
the name of 'Will Shake-speare' only came
into use to any significant extent in 1598.
(It had appeared only on the long poems
in 1593/4 before then.) The Queen knew
her reign was approaching its end. Both
she and her poet had almost total contempt
for the intelligence and percipience of the
great masses, and especially that of the
barely literate middle-classes. By then
they knew that they could put out almost
anything and have it believed. The name
'Will Shake-speare' was, in itself, an
outrageous joke. Pretending that there
was a real author with such a name was
putting icing on an already monstrous cake.

There was very little in the way of 'every
other piece of evidence' that needed to be
obliterated. The poet had, since he was a
(highly precocious) child, maintained a
tight rein on his identity as a literary figure.
He had almost always worked under the
names of others, or under pure pseudonyms.
Few courtiers knew much about his work,
and hardly any knew about the full range
of his literary activities. Many probably
suspected much, but knew little.

I doubt if the Queen or her poet expected
his pseudonymity to last long. But it's hard
to tell. They could see that there were more
and more 'John-Knox' types around, who
hated everything of that nature, and would
never understand any of it. All they really
knew was that the principal facts could not
be made known, as such, around 1600, nor
for the immediately foreseeable future.
However, they made the nature of their
cover-up manifestly transparent to any
who had eyes to see. They were fully
aware that, outside the aristocracy, almost
no such people existed, and there weren't
that many inside it either.

Paul.

