What I'm going to suggest is that you look at this evidence in isolation
from everything else we know and think we know. The Folio, at least, was
published with a prominent attribution by people who can be linked to
Shakespeare of Stratford (SOS) by documentary evidence of good legal
standing - the King's license, etc. Jonson certainly knew SOS, who was in
two of his plays, so his testimonial at least is a direct statement of
attribution by a contemporary acquaintance. Meres likely wouldn't have
known SOS, but his catalog is a direct attrribution. As far as I know,
there is no direct unequivocal evidence against these documents, and in
themselves they provide no evidence that SOS was not Shakespeare the Writer
(STW).

So, the point I have been trying to make (which is getting obscured by all
the other points I'm trying to make) is that, of all the stuff we talk
about, this is evidence of a different quality. It is not as strong as
questioning Ben Jonson in person, but it is a lot stronger than, say, &quot;SOS
was an actor in the company which performed the plays of STW&quot;.

You are, of course, at liberty to disbelieve the evidence on any basis you
wish, but to get ME to question it, I'll have to see some pretty strong
stuff. The only thing I've seen which has the potential to call the
canonical publications into question *directly* is the hyphenation of the
name (although I'll give some more thought to your comment below on the
apocrypha). Some pseudonyms had hyphens; so did some proper names. A wash.

(Asides: What's the anti-Stratfordian explanation for the hyphenated name
in the cast list of Sejanus? Why would any author want his name, or even
his pseudonym, associated with the 1603 Hamlet quarto?)

There is no reason not to question the &quot;hard&quot; evidence - perjured and
mistaken testimony is common. But I do think the higher quality of the hard
evidence calls for a high quality of contrary evidence. The major response
that I've seen so far has been simply &quot;It's falsified&quot;, but this only
carries weight if you already believe the alternate candidate's case. To
accept the alternate case, you have to accept at least one of the two
strands of circumstantial evidence - that SOS could not have been STW, or
that the alternate candidate was clearly STW. (Re-reading, I see I haven't
dealt with the second strand at all; you'll be grateful to know that I'm
getting late for work, so I'll just say &quot;same as I said for the first
strand&quot;. Hard to believe I re-read this stuff before I send it, isn't it?)

I'm generally familiar with the case against SOS, and I find it
unpersuasive. Surely there are gaps in his biography, and there are some
items which call out for explanation. But explanations are available. They
are invariably &quot;circumstantial&quot; - we've already exhausted the hard evidence
above - but they seem to me to be at least as strong, and frequently
stronger, than the counter-case.

(I don't know how you feel about this issue; I'm not attributing any of the
following arguments to you.)

For example, an anti-Stratfordian might say &quot;SOS was uneducated&quot; (this is
circumstantial evidence; there is no RECORD of his having been educated).
The pro-Stratfordian will say &quot;He probably was educated&quot; (again,
circumstantial; the records for Stratford's school are not extant, so no
record could exist; John Shakespeare was in a position to send his boys to
school and seems like the kind of ambitious guy who would make sure they
did). For argument's sake we can call this a wash. Now we can bring in
&quot;tertiary&quot; evidence (&quot;SOS's daughters were illiterate&quot;&quot;No, they weren't&quot;).
At some point, we have to weigh the quality and quantity of the
circumstantial evidence on both sides and come to a conclusion, which will,
undoubtedly, be colored by our own prejudices.

I argue that what we know about theater and society in Renaissance England,
the spotty record-keeping, SOS's life, etc., etc., add up to a good
circumstantial case, consistent in itself, that SOS was STW. To my mind, it
is factually stronger and has the added benefit of &quot;feeling&quot; right to me.
You will disagree, but I hope you will see that it's not insane to hold my
position. Since reasonable people on both sides feel their circumstantial
cases are stronger, for the sake of argument, and only temporarily, let's
call them equal.

That leaves us with the hard evidence, and I submit that you must come up
with something better than &quot;my circumstantial case is stronger than yours,
so the hard evidence is obviously falsified&quot;. You should either discredit
the hard evidence directly, or build a circumstantial case so overwhelming
that the hard evidence cannot stand against it.

I think this is *possible*. The hard evidence about Marlowe's death is very
strong - coroner's report, sworn testimony, etc. - but I feel a sufficiently
strong case has been made that his death was suspicious, so I'm prepared to
believe he was murdered. I am intrigued, but not persuaded, by the
speculative theories about the reason for it.

But I simply don't think this strong a case has been made by the
anti-Stratfordians. (Or is it non-Stratfordians? What's the preferred
term?)

