recently that I took a greater interest in the authorship debate. What I
found in reading those intros was a completely consistent story of how
Shakespeare of Stratford (SOS) COULD have written the plays, although I
didn't think of it that way at the time. In retrospect, it is the sound
circumstantial case I have been referring to. I don't think those intros
answered every question to my satisfaction. For example, I find the
attribution of a few of the sources based on a few similar phrases or a
small collection of common facts to be plausible but &quot;not proved&quot;.

(This is why I find some of the non-Shakespearean arguments - like &quot;Oxford
travelled in Italy&quot; - unconvincing in isolation; it's information SOS could
have picked up in a bar - or from Oxford. The cumulative effect of many of
these arguments *could* be convincing, although I haven't found it so to
date. I'll check out your site, particularly on the Greek and Law French
you mention, and get back to you )

But I did come away with the feeling that, even if the specific source is
unknown, it was likely that SOME source - lost plays, etc. - could explain
difficult-to-get knowledge. It's not evidence, certainly not hard evidence.
Just a recognition that the author was a guy who seemed to absorb
information about the world from everywhere. This includes includes some
sources - the lower classes - that I think an aristocrat wouldn't have much
contact with; he seems to know more about kitchens and gardening than I
would expect, for example. It's not that an aristocrat COULDN'T have known
this - &quot;who's to say what he was not capable of&quot; - just that I find it
plausible he could have been a middlin' educated kid from the middle
classes.

