I've read all your posts of the last week or so, and it's obvious you mean
business, and like to do things thoroughly. So that's why I'm making a
lengthy response.

From what I've read it looks to me that you're as close to my position on
the authorship question as makes no difference - and I'm a
&quot;near-Stratfordian&quot;. I find the whole body of evidence for William (if
you're looking for a non-combative name, and dislike the anti-Strats'
&quot;Shaksper&quot;) to be a bit worrisome in the sense of being more skeletal than
it ought to be. But internally it holds up fairly well, and shows no signs
of any kind of put-up job. (Incidentally, I should point out to you what
some of your other posts suggest you do not know - namely, that all
anti-Strat theories, whatever candidate is being promoted, are based on
conspiracy. There are none based on accidental misattribution or anything of
that nature.)

Although it's of some interest to engage in newsgroup controversies, either
here or at the Shakespeare Fellowship, it's of limited value in terms of
learning anything. To get a grasp of anti-Strat theories, you have to read
the books. Those who write them are forced at least to try to make their
arguments cohere, so obviously it's where the contradictions come to light.
An example would be where Diana Price in one part of her book is trying to
make a case that the relationship between William and the Players had ended
in acrimony some time before 1610, owing to William's &quot;theft&quot; of plays,
costumes, etc - indeed her interpretation of the John Davies epigram of 1610
depends upon it. That's all very well, but obviously we are interested to
see how she will deal with the First Folio later on in the book, and with
Jonson's De Shakespeare Nostrati. Lines like &quot;I remember, the Players have
often mentioned it as an honour to Shakespeare,&quot; would be something of an
embarassment to any theory that previously promoted the idea that William
had been sent packing by the Players. It gets worse when Jonson says things
like &quot;...who choose that circumstance to commend their friend by, wherein he
most faulted&quot;. Had the Players kissed and made up with the Stratford
Sharper? She doesn't say.

But note it. It's the necessity of holding down contradictory theories,
which is bound to happen in a book-length polemic, that brings to light the
kind of scholarship that you've already called &quot;intellectually dishonest&quot;.
Stay alert and you'll find many more examples. On a newsgroup, you get
arguments about bits and pieces, never a theory that tries to cover the
whole case. And there are some Oxfordians who you might even suspect of
making a speciality of not covering the whole case. If you're going across
to the Shakespeare Fellowship, watch out for the pick-and-choose tacticians.
Yes, they've read Ogburn, but they do not necessarily agree with everything
in it, or in Price, or in Whalen, or in Sobran, as they are quick to tell
you, but they can make a big argument about this thing or that thing. It
makes them very difficult to pin down. A month later you might find them
arguing some point that is dependent on assumptions that are in complete
contradiction to the assumptions needed for the point they are making now.
How will you remember?

No, you've got to go for the books. And focus on the Oxfordians, not because
they have the best case (which they haven't), but because they have the most
popular candidate. Oxfordian books are written by the best Oxfordians, and
I do not mean best in the sense of having necessarily the most compelling
arguments, but the best in the sense of being able to string sentences and
paragraphs into a comprehensible polemic - which obviously saves you time.
You've already reached p 62 on Price's book, so I'd recommend keeping on
with that all the way to the end. Although she doesn't identify herself as
an Oxfordian, I suspect that she is. I would guess that her book is the
first of a projected pair, the first having the objective of demolishing
&quot;Shaksper's&quot; claims, and the second replacing him with Oxford. At the moment
she has the biggest reputation in the anti-Strat world, though I'm not quite
sure why. The general opinion is that her book is very well written, but it
didn't impress me in those terms. In fact, I found some parts of it clumsy
and amateurish. Sobran's Alias Shakespeare is more readable, slicker, and
has a tone that is more agreeable. Sobran is a bit unusual in not apparently
suffering from William-hatred, a disease that has both Price and Ogburn in a
continual fever. Their compulsive sniping at &quot;Shaksper&quot; becomes really
tiresome after a while, because it doesn't actually help their case, and
just makes you wonder about their psychological health. Sobran has nothing
against William as such, and doesn't try to belittle him at every turn. He
just doesn't think he's the author, that's all. But he writes better than
Price.

And so too, surprisingly, does Ogburn. He's the crankiest of them, but you
can forgive him quite a lot because it's obvious that it's been a lifetime's
work for him, and that his passion for Shakespeare and for English history
is genuine. In some places he's actually pretty good, especially when Oxford
is kept out of it. The Armada crisis is one example, where he builds quite
a vivid narrative. Also good on hawking, which is one of his own personal
interests.

But - important point - when reading the Oxfordians, you cannot take
anything on trust. However factual some fact appears to be, you must have
the means of checking. So keep at at least some Strat books close to hand.
If you can get it, E.K Chambers' Facts and Problems. He is the most
comprehensive cataloguer of the factual material, and also the most honest,
in my opinion.

Judging from what you've written so far, I wouldn't say that there is much
hope of your being swayed by anti-Strat theories. Someday someone will do a
study of anti-Stratfordianism as a phenomenon, or I hope they will, but I
would say that there is a certain percentage of people disposed by nature to
be attracted to it. If you are not one of those, and I don't think you are,
the final effect of all your reading will be nil.

Buffalo

