kinds of replies I've gotten, here and in the SF discussion groups,
and with what I've read of research on &quot;the Oxfordian question.&quot; It
seems to be a matter of interpreting the plays. Before thinking of
Oxford as Shakespeare, the plays could only be read shallowly, for
these Oxfordians, and after thinking of Oxford as Shakespeare, they
began to take on a hidden depth. Obviously those who already felt
Shakespeare was &quot;deep,&quot; also feeling confident about the correctness
of the &quot;Stratfordian&quot; biography, didn't feel any need for a change.
