Just to re-inforce the point, I emailed Diana Price several months ago with
two queries, but didn't get a reply. I tried again yesterday, and got her
reply this morning. She had said in her book that Shakespeare was one of the
least cited actors in the extant cast lists. I asked her what cast lists she
was talking about, since the only cast lists I've ever heard of are those
attached to Jonson's published plays. I can't quote a private email
directly, but her one-sentence reply was that she didn't know of any others.
This was followed by several more sentences detailing other kinds of
evidence - allusions in poems, names appearing in stage directions,
theatrical wills, etc - none of which qualify as &quot;extant cast lists&quot;, of
course.

The second query was about her assertion that there was corrupt and
unauthorized version of 3 Henry VI that had been put on some time prior to
the publication of Groatsworth. I asked where and when this performance took
place, and how we know the text was corrupt and unauthorized. Her reply was
that, yes, there is a corrupt text; the play had been performed &quot;sundrie
times&quot; by Pembroke's men, according to the record (which we know already),
and that the play was obviously written by 1592, since a line from it is
quoted in Groatsworth (which we also know). And that's all. No text - and no
clue as to why she thinks it was either corrupt or unauthorized.

The point is that if false claims like these are made on newsgroups, they
will be shot down immediately. But when they appear in books they circulate
indefinitely, and are read and believed by much larger numbers of people.
They will be absorbed into anti-Strat dogma. And that's why, if you want to
get a grasp of the authorship debate, you really have to go for where this
stuff originates - the books. You just have to read Price, Sobran, Whalen,
Ogburn, etc, and make extensive notes as you go. And, as these examples
illustrate, you have to be alert. Hardly a page will go by without our
author trying to slip something through your guard.

