play. The First Part of the Contention appeared in print in 1594, and the
The Whole Contention appeared in 1619. Also unfortunately for you, Ms Price
was referring to performances that took place several years before either
publication appeared. What texts were used for those pre-Groatsworth
performances, whether they were inferior versions of an already existing
text, or the true version as written by Shakespeare, cannot be known.
Nor can it be known whether or not they were authorized. The 1600 quarto
of Henry VI Part 3 tells us the play was &quot;sundry times acted by the Right
Honourable the Earle of Pembrooke his seruantes'&quot;, and it would reasonable
to say that those performances at least were authorized. What other
performances there might have been that were not authorized, neither you nor
Ms Price is in any position to know.

